thern rebellion. In this highly originalcontribution to Civil War and gender history, Lorien Foote reveals that these internalbattles were fought against the backdrop of manhood. Clashing ideals ofmanliness produced myriad conflicts, as when educated, refined, and wealthyofficers (“gentlemen”) found themselves commanding a hard-drinking group offighters (“roughs”)-a dynamic that often resulted in violence and even death. Basedon extensive research into heretofore ignored primary sources, The Gentlemen and the Roughs uncoversholes in our understanding of the men who fought the Civil War and the societythat produced them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aHonorzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aMasculinityzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aSocial classeszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aSocial conflictzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aSoldierszUnited StatesxSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aViolencezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / Civil War Period (1850-1877).2bisacsh  a1865.  aCivil.  aConfederates.  aDuring.  aGentlemen.  aInternal.  aNorths.  aRoughs.  aSouthern.  aUnion.  aWar.  aagainst.  aantagonisms.  aarmy.  aarmylike.  abelow.  abooksThe.  abubbled.  aclaim.  aclass.  acohesive.  aconflicting.  adifferences.  adistracted.  adivisions.  aenough.  aextensive.  afissures.  afought.  afour.  afractiousness.  afrom.  afront.  agrueling.  aheretofore.  aholes.  aideological.  aignored.  ainto.  aorder.  apersonalities.  apresumably.  aprimary.  aproduced.  aquelling.  arebellionBased.  arecords.  aregimental.  aregional.  aresearch.  arife.  asociety.  asourcescourts-martial.  asprangappeared.  asurface.  athat.  athem.  auncov